snippet.textDisplay:
Okay, the script is due some respect. "Long in the tooth" comes from a reference to horses' gums receding as they age (making their tooths appear longer). This is also where the expression "don't look a gift horse in the mouth" comes from (you would inspect a horse as a prospective purchase by examining its teeth, and it would be rude to do this if the horse is a gift).

And I think most people know that sending something "off to the glue factory" is a reference to the old practice of selling a horse which is too old to work to be killed so that its connective tissues and chitin deposits could be used to make glue. So the glue factory bit was a call back to the "long in the tooth" reference earlier in the story.

That's good writing, if perhaps morbid when you think about it too closely.
